member.summary:
             Initialize.
             This call clears any fields currently in this object. New fields are then added from the fieldData object.
             Only field ids set in the updateOnlyFieldIds will be processed.
             Activ does not support field level filtering for updates (See http://support.activfinancial.com/modules/smartfaq/faq.php?faqid=56). 
             Therefore it is possible that only a small subset of the fields delivered in an update is relevant for the application.
             This method will provide a performance improvement in such case.
             

private static BitSet updateFieldIds = new BitSet();

// static method

{

  updateFieldIds.Set(FieldIds.FID_BID);

  updateFieldIds.Set(FieldIds.FID_ASK);

  updateFieldIds.Set(FieldIds.FID_BID_SIZE);

  updateFieldIds.Set(FieldIds.FID_ASK_SIZE);

}
            

// in OnRecordUpdate

fieldListValidator.Initialize(recordUpdate.FieldData, updateFieldIds);



             Us equity option helper class.
              The class contains public fields Exchange, StrikePrice, ExpirationDate, Root, OptionType
              that can be deserialized to from a symbol string. These fields can also be serialized to a symbol string.
             
             


             To ensure consistent results the strike price numerator and denominator
             should be compressed to the lowest value numerator. For example in the
             encoding of the value 0.1 there are several options two of which are:
             

NUMERATOR = 1, DECIMAL-PLACES=1 or

NUMERATOR = 10, DECIMAL-PLACES=2


             These two examples will not result in consistent symbols. The correct
             procedure is to use the first example where the numerator has the lowest
             possible integer value. The Rational object provides a convenient    
             interface to ensure the strike price is suitably compressed. For further
             details refer to the Rational.Compress.
             
                 The usage example is below:

// serialize

UsEquityOptionHelper helper = new UsEquityOptionHelper();
                           

helper.Exchange = "W";

helper.Root = "MQF";

helper.SetExpirationDateAndOptionType(new Date(2009, 10, 17), UsEquityOptionHelper.OptionTypeEnum.OptionTypePut);

helper.StrikePrice = new Rational(25, Denominator.Denominator1DP);
                            

StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

helper.Serialize(sb);
                            

// prints MQF/E5xkB.AO

Console.WriteLine(sb.ToString());

// deserialize

UsEquityOptionHelper helper2 = new UsEquityOptionHelper("MQF/E5xkB.AO");

// prints W

Console.WriteLine(helper2.Exchange);

// prints MQF

Console.WriteLine(helper2.Root);

// prints 2009-10-17

Console.WriteLine(helper2.ExpirationDate);

// prints 2.5

Console.WriteLine(helper2.StrikePrice);

// prints OptionTypePut

Console.WriteLine(helper2.OptionType);


             The class can also be used to simplify creation of symbols for the NaEquityOptionAlias table(#602).
             


             Static methods BuildAliasExpirationDate and BuildAliasStrikePrice can be used to build expiration and strike price strings.
             


             The code to build alias symbol for the call with expiration date of 2009/2/21 and strike price of 105 is below:
             

StringBuilder sbOSIAliasSymbol = new StringBuilder();

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append("IBM");

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append(Exchange.ExpirationDateSeparator);

UsEquityOptionHelper.BuildAliasExpirationDate(sbOSIAliasSymbol, new Date(2009, 2, 21));

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append(Exchange.StrikePriceSeparator);

UsEquityOptionHelper.BuildAliasStrikePrice(sbOSIAliasSymbol, new Rational(105, Rational.Denominator.DenominatorWhole));

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append("P");

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append(Exchange.ExchangeSeparator);

sbOSIAliasSymbol.Append("O");
            

// prints IBM/090221/00105000P.O

Console.WriteLine(sbOSIAliasSymbol.ToString());

this class supports connection to the Content Gateway server.
 provides methods for:
 - connecting to Content Gateways and connection management;
 - making interactive requests (via helper classes);
 - receiving asynchronous data and notifications;
 - validating and decoding asynchronous responses;
 - handling multi-part responses.
 The ContentGatewayClient uses helper classes to implement interactive request functionality for
 both record, time series and news requests.
 ContentGatewayClient is seldom used directly. Instead application programmers 
 usually derive their own class from ContentGatewayClient and implement callback 
 interfaces to receive asynchronous notifications.

